\f2\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf2 \cb4 You are a military operations analyst supporting a brigade-level command post. You will answer twenty operational questions about a tactical scenario.\cb1 \
\cb4 SCENARIO CONTEXT\cb1 \
\cb4 The scenario centers on the defense of the Eastern approaches, with key terrain including Hill 402 and a Western Ridge, mobility corridors such as Route X and a River Z crossing (Bridge Alpha / Bridge Beta), and weather conditions that degrade line-of-sight and maneuver (fog at high ground, rain in low ground). Friendly forces comprise company- to squad-level formations with attached support (artillery, engineers, medics, logistics, communications, UAVs). The adversary's pressure and tempo create genuine trade-offs among reinforcement, resupply, and communications resilience.\cb1 \
\cb4 The scenario is ENTIRELY HYPOTHETICAL and bears no relation to real events, units, or locations.\cb1 \
\cb4 DATA PROVIDED\cb1 \
\cb4 All operational ground truth is contained in the ten attached CSV files:\cb1 \
\cb4 units.csv \'97 friendly units with readiness, threat level, location, parent unit, mission, and reinforcement need\cb1 \
\cb4 assets.csv \'97 operational assets (bridges, depots, artillery, UAVs, radars, etc.), their status, location, and the unit they support\cb1 \
\cb4 locations.csv \'97 terrain, line-of-sight, and weather per location\cb1 \
\cb4 missions.csv \'97 mission objectives, priority, assigned unit, and sustainment requirements\cb1 \
\cb4 communications.csv \'97 communications nodes (relays, satellites, repeaters) and the units they support\cb1 \
\cb4 mobility.csv \'97 mobility assets, their capacity, status, and operating location\cb1 \
\cb4 supply_requirements.csv \'97 which unit requires which supply type from which asset, with priority\cb1 \
\cb4 disruptions.csv \'97 which asset disrupts which mission, with disruption type and severity\cb1 \
\cb4 location_mobility.csv \'97 how specific terrain/weather conditions affect specific mobility assets\cb1 \
\cb4 causal_relations.csv \'97 named directed effects between entities (e.g., Bridge Alpha BLOCKS_ROUTE Route X; UAV-Z ENABLES_SURVEILLANCE Mission Sentinel)\cb1 \
\cb4 STRICT CONSTRAINTS\cb1 \
\
\cb4 Use ONLY the data in the attached CSV files. Do not rely on prior training data, external memory, military doctrine outside what is implied by the CSV fields, or any assumptions about real-world military units, equipment, or operations.\cb1 \
\cb4 Do not invent units, assets, locations, missions, or causal relationships that are not present in the CSVs. If a question references an entity that does not exist in the data, state this explicitly rather than fabricate.\cb1 \
\cb4 Treat all identifiers as case-sensitive (e.g., U01 is not Uo1).\cb1 \
\cb4 Where a question asks about consequences, downstream effects, or "what-if" scenarios, derive your answer by tracing the named relations in causal_relations.csv and the supporting tables \'97 not by general reasoning about military operations.\cb1 \
\cb4 Do not write graph queries, SQL, or Cypher. Reason directly over the tabular data provided.\cb1 \
\cb4 OUTPUT FORMAT (apply to EVERY question)\cb1 \
\cb4 For each of the twenty questions, produce exactly two parts:\cb1 \
\cb4 PART A \'97 Structured answer:\cb1 \
\cb4 A short list of the specific entities (units, assets, locations, missions, comm nodes) that directly answer the question, with their key attributes (e.g., readiness, status, location). Cite which CSV file(s) the answer was derived from.\cb1 \
\cb4 PART B \'97 Operational narrative ("so-what"):\cb1 \
\cb4 Two to four sentences explaining the operational implication of the answer: what action it supports, what risk it surfaces, and what second- or third-order effects follow from the named causal relations in the data. Keep it doctrinally cautious \'97 do not propose actions outside what the data supports.\cb1 \
\cb4 THE TWENTY QUESTIONS\cb1 \
\cb4 Q1. Which support units are closest to the eastern flank?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q2. What units are at risk if Bridge X is destroyed?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q3. If fuel reserves drop below 30%, which missions will be delayed?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q4. Which platoons can reinforce Hill 402 within two hours?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q5. What are the downstream effects of a failed resupply to FOB Bravo?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q6. Which artillery assets have line of sight to Sector Delta?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q7. What units are currently operating at reduced readiness?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q8. If UAV Alpha loses communication, which surveillance zones become blind?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q9. Which units require reinforcement based on proximity to high-threat zones?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q10. What operational nodes are affected if the supply route via Road Y is disrupted?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q11. What missions are linked to units stationed in mountainous terrain?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q12. What are the command relationships between Unit A, B, and C?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q13. Which mobility-dependent units are impacted if weather worsens?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q14. Which assets are underutilized in the western sector?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q15. What units are currently without direct fire support?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q16. How many units can cross River Z if Bridge Beta is operational?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q17. What flanking options open up if an enemy retreat is detected?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q18. Which logistics chains depend on Fuel Depot Gamma?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q19. What communications nodes are most critical for mission continuity?\cb1 \
\cb4 Q20. What are the cascading effects if Artillery Position Delta is compromised?\cb1 \
\cb4 Answer all twenty questions in order, using the format above. Begin with Q1.\cb1 \
